Every now and then the rich light breaking through an opening or a gateway‚ as of some mighty confla- gration, the view upwards towards the Alban Mount being dark as night. At length I cleared ¹ the town, and for a few moments enjoyed a sight which one can see only now and then—a body of thick, palpable, dazzling light, reached from the eye to the sun, and filled the whole western horizon with intense and awful splendour. Anon it faded ; and after looking at the tomb of the Horatii and Curiatii, which I found, and attempted to sketch— thought to be the tomb of Aruns, son of Porsenna —walked slowly back to the inn to cool and dine. . . . .
